Re-analysis of CC G2F1 to study crossover interference

Andrew P Morgan

15 April 2025

Motivation

Crossover interference influences the recombination landscape in many taxa. The strength of interference is modulated by genetic background, sex and other factors. We have previously shown that interference varies with genotype and age in male mice (Morgan & Payseur (2024) Genetics 10.1093/genetics/iyae146). Although we showed that a model of interference that accounts for non-interferening crossovers (interference escape) fit the data better than a model of interference without escape, we were not able to reliably estimate the proportion of non-interfering crossovers. Our study was also limited to male meiosis. Here we extend the MCMC framework developed in our previous work to study interference in an 8-way outcross including both male and female meioses, accounting for interference escape.

Experimental design

The Collaborative Cross is a panel of recombinant inbred lines (RIL) created from 8-way intercrosses between mouse strains A/J (A), C57BL6/J (B), 129/SvImJ (C), NOD/ShiLtJ (D), NZO/HlLtJ (E), CAST/EiJ (F), PWK/PhJ (G) and WSB/EiJ (H). We refer to the initial generations of breeding as a funnel. Each funnel is uniquely defined by a permutation of the 8 founder strains (for example, BFGDEAHC), as shown below. The G2:F1 offspring are a mosaic of the 8 founder strains. There are 8 meioses in the first 2 outcrossing generations of the funnel (denoted G1 and G2), of which 4 occur in females and 4 in males. Because each founder strain enters the funnel exactly once, each haplotype junction observed in the G2:F1 offspring represents a crossover that can be assigned uniquely to one of these 8 meioses. Crossovers in G2, if they are transmitted, are observed with probability \(1\); crossovers in G1 can only be observed if they are transmitted again through at least one G2 meiosis, and thus are observed with probability \(\frac{3}{4}\). (Note that since the G1 and G2 meioses are mechanistically independent, the observed G1 crossovers are a random sample of all G1 crossovers.) By genotyping and reconstructing the haplotype mosaic for a pair of G2:F1 offspring we thus recover at least partial information about 8 meioses.

Collaborative Cross breeding design.

A total of \(237\) funnels \(\times~2\) per funnel \(= 434\) G2:F1 offspring were genotyped, which are the product of \(237 \times 8 = 1896\) meioses. Accounting for partial observation of G1 crossovers (conditional on transmission at G2), we expect to recover information about (\(237 \times 4\) G2 meioses) \(~+~\) (\(\frac{3}{4} \times 237 \times 4\) G1 meioses )\(~= 1659\) meioses. These results are published in Liu et al (2014) Genetics 10.1534/genetics.114.161653.

The initial analysis of the CC G2:F1 population reported a total of \(2.1993\times 10^{4}\) distinct crossovers (of which \(2.1368\times 10^{4}\) were on the autosomes) and used them to construct sex-specific genetic maps. We will load both the table of crossovers and the genetic maps and confirm that the numbers match expectations.

Prerequsites for studying crossover interference

For puposes of studying crossover intereference, we require data from whole transmitted chromosomes (hereafter, meiotic products); that is, fully phased haplotypes in the offspring For G2 meioses, this is trivial since the meiotic products are the phased haplotypes of the G2:F1 offspring. For G1 meioses, this is more complicated, since the meiotic products are the G2 offspring which were not observed directly. However, G2 genomes can be partially reconstructed from haplotypes transmitted to the G2:F1. The details of this are described in Liu et al (2010) Bioinformatics 10.1093/bioinformatics/btq187. Although there is probably useful information to be gained from meiotic products which can be reconstructed for just part of their length, modelling the censoring process seems difficult so we will limit ourselves to meiotic products that can be reconstructed unambiguously over their entire length. We will also limit the analysis to the autosomes.

Load up the table of crossovers inferred in G2 genomes (which represent products of G1 meioses; the notation is confusing). In this table, entries with missing values represent meiotic products which were completely observed, but on which there were no crossovers.

g2xos <- readr::read_csv("old_data/g2_unambigious.csv", col_names = c("funnel","meiosis","sex","chr","from","to","pos"))
g2xos$chr <- factor_chrom(g2xos$chr)
g1_obs <- select(g2xos, funnel, meiosis, chr) %>%

Modelling crossover interference

Following previous work, we will use the Housworth & Stahl (2003) Am J Hum Genet 10.1086/376610 model of crossover interference. This models the distribution of inter-crossover distances as a mixture of two processes: a pathway with interference following the gamma model; and a pathway without interference. The model has two parameters: \(\nu\), the strength of interference under the gamma model; and \(p\), the fraction of crossovers which occur via the non-interfering pathway. The data required to estimate the parameters for this model are a set of meiotic products, represented as a vector of crossover points (where an empty vector indicates a chromosome transmitted unbroken). The calculation of the likelihood is implemented in Karl Bromans xoi package (https://github.com/kbroman/xoi).

We model group-specific values of \((\nu_i, p_i)\) that are parameterised as shown below. Here \((x_1, \dots x_m)\) are a vector of covariates (which are actually just indicators). The strength of interference (\(\nu\)) and the proportion of non-interfering crossovers (\(p\)) are, by construction, restricted to the intervals \((0, \infty)\) and \((0, 1)\), respectively. Transformation to the log and logit scales, respectively, allow for estimation on a numerically-friendly domain. \[ \begin{aligned} \log(\nu_i) &= \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 + \dots + \beta_m x_m \\ \text{logit}(p_i) &= \alpha_1 x_1 + \alpha_2 x_2 + \dots + \alpha_m x_m \end{aligned} \] We estimate \(\theta_i = (\alpha_1, \dots, alpha_m; \beta_1, \dots, \beta_m)\) via MCMC as previously described. The covariance matrix is assumed to be diagonal. The proposal distribution is tuned ad hoc to ensure adequate mixing.

Results

We fit a series of models of increasing complexity. These can be split into two broad classes: first, a single value of \((\nu_i, p_i)\) is estimated for each group, representing a global interference process acting equally on all chromosomes; and second, with chromosome-specific values for \((\nu_{ij}, p_{ij})\). We will describe the design matrix for the \(\beta\)s via R-style formula notation. Models are summarized in the table below.

model_formulas <- c(
    "all_sex_gen" = "~ sex + generation",
    "all_sex_gen_full" = "~ 0 + sex:generation"
)
model_escape <- c("_no_escape","")
model_chromwise <- c("_chromwise","")
model_setup <- expand_grid( model_name = names(model_formulas), model_chromwise, model_escape ) %>%
    mutate(prefix = paste0(model_name, model_chromwise, model_escape)) %>%
    mutate(formula = model_formulas[ model_name ],
           escape = ifelse(nchar(model_escape), "no", "yes"),
           chromosome_specific = ifelse(nchar(model_chromwise), "yes","no"))

summarise_model_params <- function(model_name, ...) {
    
    ff <- paste0("model_fits/", model_name, "/out_A.rds")
    x <- readRDS(ff)
    tibble( n_groups = length(x$data$data),
            n_params = sum(!is.na(x$trace[1,])) )
    
}

    group_by(model_name, formula, escape, chromosome_specific) %>%

Summary

Assume the full model, allowing for sex- and generation-specific values of \(\nu\) and \(p\), fits the data best. (How to rigorously assess goodness-of-fit for this class of models is something I have not yet worked out.) Point estimates and \(95\%\) HPDIs for the parameters are:

The lower bound for this ratio is \(>1\) so yes, \(p\) is significantly higher in males than females.

The magnitude of the sex effect seems different in G2 than G1. Recall that the products of G1 meioses are not directly observed but can be partially reconstructed, provided they are transmitted at G2. The difference in effect size between generations suggests that the observable G1 meiotic products may be a nonrandom sample. This needs more thought. However, restricting our attention to the G2 meioses, the sex effect is actually stronger.

What about the X chromosome?

The above analyses are restricted to the autosomes. What about the X chromsome? Here we limit the analysis to female meioses, since the X chromosome is non-recombining in males, except for the pseuodoautosomal region. Haplotypes for the X are not available for G2 individuals to the analysis is further limited to G2 meioses. (Note that at least the product of the PGM meiosis can be reconstructed trivially, it is transmitted without change [outside the PAR] to the G2:F1 male.)

## make inputs for X chromosome, G2 only
xos_x <- readRDS("xos_inferred/xo_detail_all.rds") %>% subset(chr == "chrX")
x <- tidyr::expand_grid( funnel = unique(funnels$funnel),
                         meiosis = c("Mf","Mm"),
                         chr = factor_chrom( "chrX" ) ) %>%
    mutate(sex = m2s[meiosis])
xos_g2_x <- left_join(x, xos_x)

breaks_x <- subset(xos_g2_x, sex == "F") %>%
    mutate(iid = paste0(funnel, "_", meiosis)) %>% 
    split(., .$iid) %>%
    lapply(., xo_intervals_to_breaks)
saveRDS(breaks_x, "xos_inferred/breaks_by_iid_X.rds")

There should be (\(237\) funnels \(\times~2\) G2 female meioses) = \(474\) meiotic products.

breaks_x <- readRDS("xos_inferred/breaks_by_iid_X.rds")
length(breaks_x)
## [1] 474

Show estimates of interference parameters, just for the X chromosome at G2.

rez <- process_mcmc_result("model_fits/G2_chrX/out", covars = NULL, thin_factor = 5, burnin = 10e3)
plot_stahl_model_estimates(mutate(rez$predicted, sex = "F"), group_by = "sex", what = "nu")

plot_stahl_model_estimates(mutate(rez$predicted, sex = "F"), group_by = "sex", what = "p")

hpdis_x <- calc_hpdis_for_model(rez$predicted, transform = TRUE)

HPDIs are much wider than for the autosomes since there is much less data. Estimate of \(\nu\) is similar to autosomes; \(p\) is at upper boundary of the HPDI for the autosomes. Show direct comparison to full model (allowing generation-by-sex interaction) for autosomes.

hpdis_both <- bind_rows(
    mutate(hpdis, chrtype = "A"),
    mutate(hpdis_x, generation = "G2", sex = "F", chrtype = "X"),
)

subset(hpdis_both, term == "nu") %>%
    ggplot() +
    geom_pointrange(aes(x = interaction(generation, chrtype, sep = " : "), y = estimate, ymin = conf_lo, ymax = conf_hi, colour = sex),
                    position = position_dodge(width = 0.5)) +
    scale_colour_sex() +
    scale_x_discrete("generation : chromosome type") +
    scale_y_interference_nu()

subset(hpdis_both, term == "p") %>%
    ggplot() +
    geom_pointrange(aes(x = interaction(generation, chrtype, sep = " : "), y = estimate, ymin = conf_lo, ymax = conf_hi, colour = sex),
                    position = position_dodge(width = 0.5)) +
    scale_colour_sex() +
    scale_x_discrete("generation : chromosome type") +
    scale_y_interference_p()

It appears that the escape proportion is higher on the X chromosome than the autosomes with the caveat that \(p_\text{autosomes}\) and \(p_{X}\) are not estimated simultaneously.

Genetic effects at G1

The G1 generation is an incomplete diallel between the founder strains. To the extent that the partially-observed meiotic products of G1 are a reliable substrate for inference, we can use them to estimate genetic effects on crossover interference.

## annotate and save just the G1 meioses
meioses_g1 <- left_join(meioses, funnels) %>%
    subset(generation == "G1") %>%
    mutate(parents = assign_G1_parents(order, meiosis)) %>%
    mutate(mat_ss = xrenamer[ substr(parents, 1, 1) ], pat_ss = xrenamer[ substr(parents, 2, 2) ]) %>%
    mutate(parents_ss = paste0(substr(pat_ss, 1, 1), substr(mat_ss, 1, 1)))
saveRDS(meioses_g1, "xos_inferred/meioses_g1.rds")
meioses_g1 <- readRDS("xos_inferred/meioses_g1.rds")

Show the results of fitting a full model (separate values of \(\nu, p\) for every sex-genotype combination) to meiotic products from G1.

rez <- readRDS("model_fits/G1_sex_ss/out_precooked.rds")

genotype_labeller <- function(f) {
    ss <- c("d" = "dom", "m" = "mus", "c" = "cas")
    return( paste0(ss[ substr(f,1,1) ], " x ", ss[ substr(f,2,2) ]) )
}

plot_stahl_model_estimates(rez$predicted, what = "nu", group_by = "parents_ss") +
    scale_x_discrete(label = genotype_labeller)

plot_stahl_model_estimates(rez$predicted, what = "p", group_by = "parents_ss") +
    scale_x_discrete(label = genotype_labeller)

It looks like there is variation between genotypes, but less so between sexes. Construct contrasts between male and female for each genotype.

nu <- rez$coefs_nu %>% select(-.iter, -.chain) %>% as.matrix()
pp <- rez$coefs_nu %>% select(-.iter, -.chain) %>% as.matrix()

sex_contrasts <- list(
    "cd" = c(rep(0, 0), -1,1, rep(0,12)),
    "cm" = c(rep(0, 2), -1,1, rep(0,10)),
    "dc" = c(rep(0, 4), -1,1, rep(0, 8)),
    "dd" = c(rep(0, 6), -1,1, rep(0, 6)),
    "dm" = c(rep(0, 8), -1,1, rep(0, 4)),
    "mc" = c(rep(0,10), -1,1, rep(0, 2)),
    "md" = c(rep(0,12), -1,1, rep(0, 0))
)

g1_sex_effs <- bind_rows(
    lapply(sex_contrasts, function(f) calc_hpdi_from_vector(nu %*% f)) %>%
        bind_rows(.id = "genotype") %>%
        mutate(term = "nu"),
    lapply(sex_contrasts, function(f) calc_hpdi_from_vector(pp %*% f)) %>%
        bind_rows(.id = "genotype") %>%
        mutate(term = "p")
)

Below are \(95\%\) HPDIs for male-female comparisons for \(\nu,p\) within genotype. For \(\nu\) the result is a ratio; for \(p\), an odds ratio. Dashed grey line indicates the null.

mutate_if(g1_sex_effs, is.numeric, exp) %>%
    ggplot() +
    geom_pointrange(aes(x = genotype, y = estimate, ymin = conf_lo, ymax = conf_hi)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 1, colour = "grey", lty = "dashed") +
    scale_y_continuous(trans = "log2") +
    scale_x_discrete(label = genotype_labeller) +
    facet_grid(. ~ term) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

We do not detect a difference between sexes, within genotypes. The power of this analysis is limited by small sample size and by whatever additional uncertainty is added by the incomplete observation of G1 meiotic products via their transmission at G2.
